ABSTRACT

We present a complete materials development framework for extraterrestrial structural metals, fundamentally reimagined for strategic autonomy beyond low Earth orbit. The blueprint centers on three primary alloy systems designed for graduated ISRU dependence:

1. PSM-1 (Primary Structural Material - Transit Grade): Ultrafine-grained Al-Mg-Zn-Cu-Ag crossover alloy with T-phase [Mg₃₂(Zn,Al)₄₉] nanoprecipitates. Density: 2.65 g/cm³. Radiation tolerance: 10 dpa design limit (24 dpa ultimate threshold). Optimized for Earth-launched deep space vehicles where mass efficiency dominates.
2. PSM-1B (Primary Structural Material - Lunar Grade): Iron-strengthened Al-Mg-Fe-Mn alloy utilizing 100% in-situ resources. Density: 2.70 g/cm³. Yield strength: 450 MPa. Zero dependence on Earth-supplied trace elements. Designed for permanent lunar infrastructure where supply chain resilience is paramount.
3. HTSM-1 (High-Temperature Structural Material): Ti-V-Nb-Zr-Al refractory high-entropy alloy with integrated Functionally Graded Material (FGM) thermal protection. Density: 6.2 g/cm³. Service temperature: -200°C to +650°C (core), with ceramic outer layer surviving >1500°C peak.

All systems are optimized for molten regolith electrolysis with oxygen co-production, now incorporating thermal integration for 14-day lunar night survival and anode erosion management strategies. The development pathway integrates physics-constrained AI discovery, autonomous rapid prototyping, low-gravity manufacturing validation, and a dual-track certification framework targeting Artemis Phase-2 habitats and Mars transit vehicles.

Key Innovations in v4.0:

· PSM-1B ISRU-pure variant eliminating Zn/Ag import dependency
· Low-gravity powder delivery systems (gas-flow-assisted and slurry-based)
· Functionally graded metal-ceramic thermal protection
· Helium management modeling for extended radiation lifetime
· Bio-ISRU symbiosis connecting materials production to life support

