2.2 Molten Regolith Electrolysis (MRE) - Primary Pathway

2.2.1 Process Fundamentals

MRE is direct electrolytic reduction of molten regolith to produce metals and oxygen. The process operates at 1600-1650°C, above the liquidus temperature of anorthite-rich highland regolith.

2.2.1.1 Electrochemical Principles

Cell voltage requirement:

E_{cell} = E^0 + \eta_{anode} + \eta_{cathode} + iR_{electrolyte}

For alumina reduction:

· $E^0$ (Al₂O₃ → Al + ¾O₂) = 2.20 V at 1600°C
· $\eta_{anode}$ (oxygen evolution overpotential) = 0.4 V
· $\eta_{cathode}$ (metal nucleation overpotential) = 0.2 V
· $iR$ (ohmic loss in molten salt) = 1.4 V at 5000 A/m², 5 cm electrode gap

Total operating voltage: 4.2-4.8 VDC

2.2.1.2 Current Efficiency

Theoretical current efficiency limited by:

1. Electronic conductivity in molten slag (reduces faradaic efficiency)
2. Metal re-oxidation at anode (back reactions)
3. Gas bubble entrapment at electrodes

Target performance: 85-90% current efficiency

2.2.2 Cell Design and Materials

2.2.2.1 Baseline Configuration (TRL 6)

Component Material Lifetime Replacement Interval
Anode Iridium (Ir) 500-1000 hours Every 3-6 months
Cathode Tungsten (W) 2000+ hours Annual
Crucible Molybdenum (Mo) 1000+ hours Semi-annual
Electrolyte Molten regolith + CaF₂ flux Continuous Top-up only
Current leads Molybdenum 5000+ hours As needed

Iridium anode justification: Iridium is the only material demonstrated to withstand oxygen evolution in molten oxide electrolytes at 1600°C without rapid consumption. NASA/MSFC testing (2010-2012) achieved TRL 6 with iridium anodes showing "no visible degradation" after extended operation.

2.2.2.2 Advanced Anode Development (v4.0 Addition)

Problem: Iridium is rare ($40,000-60,000/kg) and imported from Earth. Even with 500-hour lifetimes, spares mass penalty reduces leverage.

Solution pathways:

Pathway TRL Advantages Challenges Timeline
Self-forming spinel anodes 2-3 Infinite life, ISRU materials Requires precise pO₂ control Phase 2 (2030+)
Cr-based cermets 4-5 Lower cost, proven in Al smelting Cr volatility in vacuum Phase 1 (2027-2029)
Consumable carbon 9 TRL 9, lowest energy CO byproduct (no O₂), frequent replacement Immediate

Proposal 2.1: Adopt hybrid anode strategy for Phase 1:

· Carbon anodes for initial production (maximizing reliability, accepting CO byproduct)
· Iridium anodes for oxygen-critical missions (when O₂ is primary product)
· Self-forming spinel R&D as Phase 2 advanced development

2.2.3 Chemical Reactions by Feedstock

2.2.3.1 Highland Regolith (Anorthite-rich)

Composition: CaAl₂Si₂O₈ (anorthite) with Mg, Fe impurities

Primary reduction:

2Al_2O_3(l) \xrightarrow[1600^\circ C]{electrolysis} 4Al(l) + 3O_2(g)

Secondary reactions (controlled):

2MgO(s) \xrightarrow[1600^\circ C]{in\ melt} 2Mg(g) + O_2(g)


SiO_2(l) \xrightarrow[]{electrolysis} Si(l) + O_2(g)


FeO(l) \rightarrow Fe(l) + \frac{1}{2}O_2(g)

Mg recovery: Mg vapor evolved at cathode, condensed at 500°C in cold trap

Si control: Limited to <2% Si in melt to prevent cathode passivation (silicide formation)

2.2.3.2 Mare Regolith (Basalt-rich)

Composition: FeTiO₃ (ilmenite), pyroxenes, olivine

Primary reductions:

2FeTiO_3(s) \rightarrow 2Fe(l) + 2Ti(l) + 3O_2(g)


(Mg,Fe)_2SiO_4 \rightarrow 2(Mg,Fe)(l) + Si(l) + 2O_2(g)

Vanadium extraction (from pyroxene):
(Ca,Mg,Fe)(Mg,Fe,Al)(Si,Al)_2O_6 \rightarrow V_2O_5 \rightarrow 2V(l) + 2.5O_2(g)

Zirconium extraction (from zircon):
ZrSiO_4(s) \xrightarrow[]{1600^\circ C} Zr(l) + Si(l) + 2O_2(g)

2.2.4 Thermal Integration for Lunar Night Survival (v4.0 Addition)

Challenge: The 14-day lunar night drops temperatures to -173°C. Reheating an MRE cell from cryogenic to 1600°C requires enormous energy—more than the cell consumes during operation.

Solution: Molten salt thermal storage

Parameter Value
Storage medium MgF₂-CaF₂ eutectic (m.p. 972°C)
Operating temperature 1000-1200°C
Storage capacity 500 kWh/m³
Insulation Multilayer (MLI) + regolith berm
Heat loss <5% per 14 days

Operation during lunar day (14 Earth days):

· MRE operates at full capacity
· Excess solar power heats thermal storage to 1200°C

Operation during lunar night (14 Earth days):

· MRE in standby (electrodes retracted)
· Thermal storage maintains cell >1000°C
· <50 kWh required for restart at dawn

Mass penalty: 0.5 kg thermal storage per kg metal produced (vs. 2 kg solar array without storage)

