CHAPTER 4: MANUFACTURING-BY-DESIGN

4.1 Foundational Principles of In-Situ Manufacturing

Manufacturing in space differs fundamentally from terrestrial production. The absence of gravity-driven convection, the vacuum environment, and the constraints of available energy and feedstock require a manufacturing-by-design approach where the final component properties are determined as much by the production process as by the alloy chemistry.

4.1.1 Design for In-Situ Manufacturing (DFISM) Principles

Principle Implication
Minimize gravity dependence Powder delivery must not rely on gravity flow
Embrace vacuum Exploit vacuum for degassing, avoid processes requiring atmosphere
Thermal integration Use waste heat, plan for thermal cycling
Modularity Equipment must be repairable/replaceable with ISRU components
In-process inspection No offline quality control; build in monitoring
Recyclability Powder reuse, support structures remelted

4.1.2 Manufacturing Process Flow

```
                    REGOLITH
                        ↓
              BENEFICIATION & MRE
                        ↓
                 METAL INGOTS
                        ↓
