CHAPTER 6: CONCLUSIONS AND FUTURE DIRECTIONS

6.1 Summary of Achievements

This thesis has presented a comprehensive framework for the development of next-generation spacecraft structural metals specifically optimized for extraterrestrial environments and in-situ resource utilization. The NGSSM-DS v4.0 blueprint represents a fundamental paradigm shift from Earth-optimized materials to system-optimized materials that account for the full mission context: launch mass, radiation durability, ISRU compatibility, manufacturing constraints, and strategic autonomy.

The primary technical achievements of this work are:

1. Dual-Alloy Strategy with Strategic Autonomy

We have defined two primary alloy systems tailored to different mission phases:

· PSM-1 (Transit Grade): Al-Mg-Zn-Cu-Ag ultrafine-grained alloy with T-phase nanoprecipitates, achieving 600 MPa yield strength and 10 dpa radiation design limit. This alloy is optimized for Earth-launched deep space vehicles where mass efficiency justifies trace element imports.
· PSM-1B (Lunar Grade): Al-Mg-Fe-Mn alloy strengthened by Al₁₃Fe₄ intermetallics, achieving 450 MPa yield strength with 100% ISRU capability. This alloy eliminates dependence on Earth-supplied Zn, Cu, and Ag, providing strategic autonomy for permanent lunar infrastructure.
· HTSM-1: Ti-V-Nb-Zr-Al refractory high-entropy alloy with integrated functionally graded thermal protection, capable of service from -200°C to +650°C (core) with ceramic outer layer surviving >1500°C.

2. ISRU Processing Framework

We have established complete chemical pathways for metal production from lunar regolith via molten regolith electrolysis, including:

· Thermodynamic and kinetic analysis of reduction reactions
· Thermal integration strategies for 14-day lunar night survival
· Hybrid anode approach balancing reliability, oxygen production, and import dependence
· Oxygen co-production mass balance demonstrating 500 kg O₂ per 1000 kg regolith
· Bio-ISRU symbiosis connecting materials production to life support systems

3. AI-Enhanced Discovery Pipeline

The AtomAgents multi-agent system integrates physics-based constraints (DFT, CALPHAD, MD) with machine learning to accelerate alloy discovery by orders of magnitude:

· 10⁶ compositions screened per day
· Self-driving laboratory validates 100 compositions per week
· Synergistic aging simulation predicts combined radiation-thermal-mechanical damage
· ISRU scoring prioritizes strategic autonomy alongside performance

4. Manufacturing-by-Design for Space

We have developed comprehensive manufacturing protocols addressing the unique challenges of in-space production:

· Gas-flow-assisted powder delivery validated for low-gravity environments
· LPBF parameters for PSM-1/PSM-1B optimized for vacuum and reduced gravity
· EB-PBF with dual-hopper FGM capability for integrated thermal protection
· Friction stir welding as primary joining method, eliminating hot cracking in vacuum
· Powder regeneration station for closed-loop material recycling

5. Realistic Qualification Framework

Recognizing the gap between ion irradiation screening and neutron validation, we have established:

· Differentiated radiation tolerance claims (10 dpa design, 24 dpa ultimate for PSM-1)
· Helium management modeling to address transmutation effects
· Synergistic aging test protocols combining radiation, thermal cycling, and stress
· Dual-track certification pathway: traditional MMPDS plus digital twin acceleration
· Early engagement with qualification authorities (NASA OSD, FAA-AST)

