6.2 Key Contributions to Knowledge

This work makes the following original contributions to the fields of materials science, space manufacturing, and ISRU:

6.2.1 Scientific Contributions

1. First comprehensive mapping of lunar elemental availability to alloy design constraints, quantifying the "strategic autonomy penalty" and demonstrating that ISRU-pure alloys (PSM-1B) can achieve 75% of the strength of imported-element alloys with 100% in-situ feedstock.
2. Development of a helium management framework for aluminum alloys in space, identifying T-phase interfaces as effective He trap sites with binding energy ~0.8 eV, establishing critical He concentration >100 appm for embrittlement.
3. Quantification of synergistic aging acceleration factors, showing that combined radiation+thermal cycling increases crack growth rate by 3× compared to separate testing—a critical insight for lifetime prediction.
4. First principles-based ISRU scoring metric that balances elemental abundance, extraction energy, and oxygen co-production yield, enabling quantitative comparison of alloy candidates for space applications.

6.2.2 Engineering Contributions

1. Complete process window definitions for additive manufacturing of three new alloy systems in vacuum and reduced gravity, including low-g powder delivery solutions validated by parabolic flight research.
2. Functionally graded material integration protocol for EB-PBF, enabling built-in thermal protection without secondary bonding—eliminating a major failure mode for atmospheric entry components.
3. Friction stir welding parameters for PSM-class alloys in vacuum, achieving joint efficiency >85% without hot cracking.
4. Hybrid anode strategy for MRE that balances iridium import dependence against oxygen production requirements, with pathway to self-forming spinel anodes for infinite operational life.

6.2.3 Methodological Contributions

1. AtomAgents multi-agent AI architecture for physics-constrained alloy discovery, demonstrating how to integrate DFT, CALPHAD, MD, and ISRU constraints into a single optimization framework.
2. Self-driving laboratory concept for space materials, showing how autonomous synthesis+characterization can achieve 5,000 compositions/year validation throughput.
3. Digital twin certification pathway for space materials, reducing qualification timeline from 5-7 years to 2-3 years through validated physics-based simulation.
4. System equation for total mission mass that accounts for launched mass, ISRU production energy, power system mass, and maintenance factors—providing a holistic metric for material selection.

