Radiation tolerance (10 dpa design) Ion data extrapolation Factor of 2
He management at T-phase interfaces DFT calculations only Requires TEM validation
Low-g powder flow performance Parabolic flight analogs Scale-up risk

6.3.2 ISRU Assumptions

The ISRU pathway assumes successful development of molten regolith electrolysis at scale—a technology currently at TRL 4-5. Key risks:

· Anode lifetime in 1600°C silicate melts
· Product purity control (especially Si in Al)
· Thermal management through lunar night
· Solids handling in low gravity

6.3.3 Economic Uncertainties

The mass leverage calculations assume specific solar array mass (0.4 kg/kW) and equipment masses that may not reflect first-generation lunar industrial equipment. Early systems will likely be heavier, reducing leverage ratios.

6.3.4 Certification Timeline

The dual-track certification pathway assumes acceptance of digital twin data by qualification authorities—a precedent that does not yet exist for crewed spaceflight hardware.

