6.5 Concluding Remarks

The vision of a permanent human presence beyond Earth hinges on our ability to live off the land—to manufacture structures, generate oxygen, and sustain life from local resources. The NGSSM-DS framework demonstrates that this is not only possible but can be achieved with materials that outperform Earth-optimized alloys in the specific environments where they must serve.

The key insight of this work is that strategic autonomy is a material property. By designing alloys around what is available—not what we wish were available—we eliminate supply chain vulnerabilities that could otherwise cripple a lunar base or Mars mission. PSM-1B may have lower strength than its Earth-import-dependent cousin, but its ability to be manufactured entirely from lunar regolith makes it the true "Moon material." PSM-1 remains valuable for Earth-launched deep space vehicles, but for permanence, we must prioritize what we can make in situ.

The technical challenges ahead are substantial: validating radiation tolerance, scaling ISRU processes, certifying new alloys, and proving manufacturing in low gravity. But the foundation is laid. The chemical pathways are defined. The AI tools are ready. The manufacturing protocols are specified.

What remains is execution—moving from blueprint to lunar factory. The Artemis Generation has the opportunity to build not just habitats and landers, but a sustainable economy beyond Earth. The materials in this thesis are the bricks and mortar of that future.

As we look toward the Moon, Mars, and the stars beyond, let us remember that the most important resource we carry is not metal or fuel, but knowledge. And knowledge, once gained, enables us to build anything, anywhere, from whatever we find.

