APPENDICES

APPENDIX A: THERMODYNAMIC FOUNDATIONS

A.1 Gibbs Free Energy of Formation for T-phase [Mg₃₂(Zn,Al)₄₉]

The T-phase (space group Fd-3m, Pearson symbol cF162) is the primary strengthening precipitate in PSM-1. Its Gibbs free energy of formation determines stability against dissolution under thermal and radiation exposure.

A.1.1 First-Principles Calculation

The formation energy is calculated using density functional theory (DFT) with the VASP code, employing the Perdew-Burke-Ernzerhof (PBE) generalized gradient approximation and projector augmented wave (PAW) pseudopotentials. A 2×2×2 k-point mesh and 520 eV cutoff energy are used for a 162-atom supercell.

\Delta G_f(T) = \Delta H_f - T\Delta S_f + \Delta G_{vib}(T)

Where:

· $\Delta H_f$: enthalpy of formation at 0 K
· $\Delta S_f$: configurational entropy (negligible for ordered phase)
· $\Delta G_{vib}$: vibrational free energy contribution

DFT result at 0 K: $\Delta H_f = -15.2 \text{ kJ/mol-atoms}$

A.1.2 Temperature Dependence

The vibrational free energy is approximated using the Debye model:

\Delta G_{vib}(T) = \frac{9}{8}k_B\Theta_D - k_BT \left[ 3\ln\left(1-e^{-\Theta_D/T}\right) - D\left(\frac{\Theta_D}{T}\right) \right]

Where $\Theta_D$ is the Debye temperature (estimated from elastic constants: $\Theta_D \approx 450$ K for T-phase). The Debye function $D(x)$ is:

D(x) = \frac{3}{x^3}\int_0^x \frac{t^3}{e^t-1} dt

Result: At 300 K, $\Delta G_{vib} \approx -1.2$ kJ/mol, giving $\Delta G_f(300K) = -16.4$ kJ/mol.

A.1.3 Phase Stability Criterion

For T-phase to be stable against dissolution into matrix:

\Delta G_f(T) < \Delta G_{matrix}(T)

The matrix solid solution free energy is given by regular solution model:

\Delta G_{matrix} = \sum_i x_i \Delta G_i^0 + RT\sum_i x_i \ln x_i + \sum_{i<j} \Omega_{ij} x_i x_j

With interaction parameters $\Omega_{Al-Zn} = 8.3$ kJ/mol, $\Omega_{Al-Mg} = -2.5$ kJ/mol, etc., T-phase remains stable up to 400°C (673 K) where $\Delta G_f \approx -8.1$ kJ/mol.

A.2 Phase Stability Calculations (CALPHAD Background)

The CALPHAD method models Gibbs free energy of each phase as function of temperature and composition.

A.2.1 Gibbs Free Energy for a Phase

For a solution phase (e.g., liquid, FCC, BCC):

G_m^\phi = \sum_i x_i G_i^{0,\phi} + RT\sum_i x_i \ln x_i + {}^{ex}G_m^\phi

Where:

· $G_i^{0,\phi}$: Gibbs free energy of pure element i in structure $\phi$
· $x_i$: mole fraction
· $RT\sum x_i \ln x_i$: ideal mixing entropy
· ${}^{ex}G_m^\phi$: excess Gibbs energy, modeled by Redlich-Kister polynomial:

{}^{ex}G_m^\phi = \sum_{i<j} x_i x_j \sum_{\nu=0}^n {}^\nu L_{ij}^\phi (x_i - x_j)^\nu

The interaction parameters ${}^\nu L_{ij}^\phi$ are temperature-dependent:

{}^\nu L_{ij}^\phi = a_\nu + b_\nu T + c_\nu T \ln T + d_\nu T^2 + ...

A.2.2 T-phase Modeling

T-phase is modeled as a line compound (stoichiometric) with narrow homogeneity range. Its Gibbs energy is expressed relative to stable elements:

G_m^{T-phase} = \sum_i y_i G_i^{0,ref} + \Delta G_f^{T-phase}

Where $y_i$ are site fractions, and $\Delta G_f^{T-phase}$ is the formation energy from DFT, adjusted to reproduce experimental phase boundaries.

A.3 Vapor Pressure and Outgassing Models

A.3.1 Vapor Pressure of Elements

Vapor pressure of pure element i is given by Clausius-Clapeyron:

\ln P_i = A_i - \frac{B_i}{T} + C_i \ln T + D_i T

For Al, Zn, Mg, Ag (relevant for PSM-1):

Element A B (K) C D (K⁻¹) Valid Range (K)
Al 13.5 36300 -0.5 0 900-1200
Zn 12.3 13100 -0.8 0 600-1000
Mg 12.8 15800 -0.7 0 700-1100
Ag 13.2 32700 -0.6 0 1000-1400

At 500°C (773 K), $P_{Al} \approx 10^{-9}$ Torr, $P_{Zn} \approx 10^{-2}$ Torr—explaining Zn loss risk in vacuum.

A.3.2 Alloy Vapor Pressure (Raoult's Law)

For ideal solution, partial pressure $p_i = x_i P_i$. For PSM-1 (x_Zn ≈ 0.04), $p_{Zn} \approx 4\times10^{-4}$ Torr at 500°C—still significant, requiring coatings or closed systems.

A.3.3 Outgassing Rate Model

Outgassing flux $J$ from surface:

J = \frac{p_i}{\sqrt{2\pi m_i k_B T}} \quad (\text{Hertz-Knudsen})

For Zn at 500°C, $J \approx 10^{17}$ atoms/m²/s → 0.1 μm/year loss—acceptable for short missions but problematic for decades.

