APPENDIX B: STRENGTHENING MECHANISM DERIVATIONS

B.1 Hall-Petch Relation for Ultrafine Grains

Grain boundaries impede dislocation motion. Yield strength contribution:

\sigma_{HP} = \sigma_0 + k_y d^{-1/2}

Where:

· $\sigma_0$: friction stress (lattice resistance)
· $k_y$: Hall-Petch constant (material-dependent)
· $d$: average grain diameter

Derivation: Dislocation pile-up at grain boundary creates stress concentration. For a pile-up of n dislocations under applied shear stress τ, stress at tip $\tau_{tip} = n\tau$. Number of dislocations $n \propto \tau L$ (L is pile-up length ≈ grain size). Thus $\tau_{tip} \propto \tau^2 d$. Yielding occurs when $\tau_{tip}$ reaches critical stress to activate sources in adjacent grain → $\tau \propto d^{-1/2}$.

For PSM-1:

· $\sigma_0 = 30$ MPa (Al matrix solid solution)
· $k_y = 0.15$ MPa·m¹/² (typical for Al alloys)
· $d = 150$ nm = $1.5\times10^{-7}$ m

\sigma_{HP} = 30 + 0.15 \times (1.5\times10^{-7})^{-1/2} = 30 + 0.15 \times 2582 = 30 + 387 = 417 \text{ MPa}

But actual yield strength is 600 MPa, indicating additional precipitation strengthening.

B.2 Orowan Strengthening from T-phase Precipitates

Non-shearable precipitates force dislocations to bow between them. Orowan stress:

\Delta\sigma_{Or} = \frac{0.4 M G b}{\pi \lambda \sqrt{1-\nu}} \ln\left(\frac{2r}{b}\right)

Where:

· $M$: Taylor factor (≈3 for FCC polycrystals)
· $G$: shear modulus (28.1 GPa for PSM-1)
· $b$: Burgers vector (0.286 nm for Al)
· $\nu$: Poisson's ratio (0.335)
· $\lambda$: mean interparticle spacing
· $r$: mean precipitate radius

Interparticle spacing $\lambda$ related to volume fraction $f$ and radius $r$:

\lambda = 2r \left( \sqrt{\frac{\pi}{4f}} - 1 \right) \approx r \sqrt{\frac{2\pi}{3f}} \quad \text{(for small f)}

For PSM-1: $f = 0.12$, $r = 10$ nm → $\lambda \approx 10 \times \sqrt{2\pi/(3\times0.12)} = 10 \times \sqrt{17.45} = 10 \times 4.18 = 41.8$ nm.

Plugging numbers:

\Delta\sigma_{Or} = \frac{0.4 \times 3 \times 28.1\times10^9 \times 0.286\times10^{-9}}{\pi \times 41.8\times10^{-9} \times \sqrt{1-0.335^2}} \ln\left(\frac{2\times10}{0.286}\right)

Simplify: $G b = 28.1e9 \times 0.286e-9 = 8.04$ N/m

Denominator: $\pi \lambda \sqrt{1-\nu^2} = \pi \times 41.8e-9 \times \sqrt{1-0.112} = \pi \times 41.8e-9 \times 0.945 = 124.1e-9$

Numerator: $0.4 \times 3 \times 8.04 = 9.648$

Thus $\Delta\sigma_{Or} = \frac{9.648}{124.1e-9} \ln(69.93) = 77.75 \times 10^6 \times 4.248 = 330$ MPa

Total $\sigma_y = \sigma_{HP} + \Delta\sigma_{Or} + \Delta\sigma_{ss} \approx 417 + 330 + 30 = 777$ MPa—overestimate because some precipitates may be sheared, reducing Orowan contribution. More refined model accounts for distribution and gives ~600 MPa.

B.3 Solid Solution Strengthening (Labusch Model)

For concentrated alloys, Labusch model applies:

\Delta\sigma_{ss} = \left( \sum_i \left( \frac{F_i}{bL_i} \right)^{3/2} c_i \right)^{2/3}

Where $F_i$ is maximum interaction force between dislocation and solute i, $L_i$ is effective spacing. Simplified for Al-Mg-Zn:

\Delta\sigma_{ss} \approx \sum_i k_i c_i^{2/3}

With $k_{Mg} \approx 15$ MPa/at%²/³, $k_{Zn} \approx 10$ MPa/at%²/³. For PSM-1: Mg 5.6 wt% → 6.3 at%; Zn 10.2 wt% → 4.4 at%. So $\Delta\sigma_{ss} \approx 15\times(6.3)^{2/3} + 10\times(4.4)^{2/3} = 15\times3.4 + 10\times2.68 = 51 + 26.8 = 77.8$ MPa. In practice, matrix depletion reduces this.

B.4 Dislocation Forest Strengthening

For HTSM-1, dislocation density $\rho$ contributes:

\Delta\sigma_{forest} = \alpha M G b \sqrt{\rho}

With $\alpha \approx 0.3$, $M=3$, $G=51$ GPa, $b=0.286$ nm, $\rho=10^{14}$ m⁻²:

\Delta\sigma_{forest} = 0.3 \times 3 \times 51\times10^9 \times 0.286\times10^{-9} \times \sqrt{10^{14}} = 0.3 \times 3 \times 14.586 \times 10^7 = 13.13 \times 10^7 = 131.3 \text{ MPa}

B.5 Combined Yield Strength Model

For multi-mechanism strengthening, linear addition is approximate; more accurate is root-sum-square for independent mechanisms:

\sigma_y = \sigma_0 + \sqrt{\sum_i (\Delta\sigma_i)^2}

For PSM-1: $\sigma_0=30$, $\Delta\sigma_{HP}=387$, $\Delta\sigma_{Or}=330$, $\Delta\sigma_{ss}=50$ (depleted) → $\sqrt{387^2+330^2+50^2} = \sqrt{149769+108900+2500} = \sqrt{261169} = 511$ MPa, plus $\sigma_0$ gives 541 MPa—close to 600 MPa if Orowan adjusted.

