APPENDIX C: RADIATION DAMAGE PHYSICS

C.1 Displacement Per Atom (dpa) Calculation

dpa quantifies radiation damage:

\text{dpa} = \frac{\phi \sigma_d N_{d,avg}}{N}

Where:

· $\phi$: fluence (particles/m²)
· $\sigma_d$: displacement cross-section
· $N_{d,avg}$: average number of displacements per primary knock-on atom (PKA)
· $N$: atomic density

For ion irradiation, SRIM/TRIM calculates displacements. For neutrons, dpa is computed via:

\text{dpa} = \int \sigma(E) \phi(E) N_d(E) dE

The Norgett-Robinson-Torrens (NRT) model gives:

N_d = \frac{0.8 T_{dam}}{2E_d}

Where $T_{dam}$ is damage energy (PKA energy minus electronic losses), $E_d$ is displacement threshold energy (~25 eV for Al, ~40 eV for Ti).

C.2 Defect Sink Strength and Recombination

Point defects (vacancies, interstitials) migrate to sinks (grain boundaries, dislocations, interfaces). Sink strength $k^2$ (m⁻²) is defined via rate theory:

\frac{\partial C_v}{\partial t} = K_0 - D_v k_v^2 C_v - \mu_r D_v C_v C_i

Where $K_0$ is defect production rate (dpa/s × atomic density), $k_v^2$ is sink strength for vacancies.

For grain boundaries: $k_{gb}^2 = \frac{15}{d^2}$ for spherical grains. For PSM-1 with d=150 nm, $k_{gb}^2 = 15/(1.5e-7)^2 = 15/2.25e-14 = 6.67e14$ m⁻². Total sink strength includes dislocations: $k_{dis}^2 = \rho_d Z_d$, with $\rho_d$ dislocation density, $Z_d \approx 1$.

C.3 Helium Management and Bubble Nucleation

Helium produced by (n,α) reactions is insoluble and precipitates into bubbles. Critical He concentration for bubble nucleation at grain boundaries:

C_{He}^{crit} = \frac{2\gamma}{k_B T \ln(Z)} \frac{1}{R_{crit}}

Where $\gamma$ is surface energy, $R_{crit}$ critical radius, $Z$ supersaturation.

Helium diffusion coefficient in Al: $D_{He} = D_0 \exp(-E_m/k_B T)$ with $E_m \approx 0.5$ eV. T-phase interfaces trap He with binding energy $E_b \approx 0.8$ eV, reducing mobility.

C.4 Swelling and Embrittlement Models

Void swelling $\Delta V/V = \sum (N_v V_v)$ where $N_v$ is void density, $V_v$ average void volume. Swelling rate $\dot{S} = (K_0 - recombination) \times \text{bias factor}$. For Al alloys, swelling accelerates above critical dpa (typically 0.5-2 dpa). PSM-1 aims to delay swelling by high sink strength.

