APPENDIX D: ISRU ELECTROCHEMISTRY

D.1 Nernst Equation and Cell Voltage

For a redox reaction $\sum \nu_O O + ne^- \rightarrow \sum \nu_R R$, equilibrium potential:

E = E^0 - \frac{RT}{nF} \ln Q

For Al₂O₃ reduction: Al₂O₃ → 2Al + ³/₂O₂, $n=6$, $E^0 = -2.20$ V at 1600°C (relative to O₂ reference). Actual cell voltage:

E_{cell} = E^0 + \eta_{anode} + \eta_{cathode} + iR

D.2 Molten Regolith Electrolysis Thermodynamics

Gibbs free energy change for oxide reduction:

\Delta G = \Delta G^0 + RT \ln\left(\frac{a_{metal}^2 P_{O_2}^{3/2}}{a_{oxide}}\right)

At 1600°C, $\Delta G^0$ for Al₂O₃ is ~900 kJ/mol, corresponding to $E^0 = -\Delta G/(nF) = -900,000/(6×96485) = -1.55$ V (vs. O₂). The tabulated 2.20 V includes temperature effects and standard state choices.

D.3 Current Efficiency and Faradaic Losses

Current efficiency $\eta_{current} = \frac{\text{moles metal produced} \times nF}{\text{total charge}}$ losses due to:

· Electronic conductivity in slag (partial reduction of multivalent ions)
· Metal re-oxidation at anode
· Gas bubble entrapment

Electronic conductivity $\sigma_e$ in molten oxide follows:

\sigma_e = \sigma_e^0 \exp(-E_a/k_B T)

At 1600°C, $\sigma_e$ can be 10-20% of ionic conductivity.

D.4 Thermal Storage and Energy Balance

Energy to maintain cell at 1600°C through lunar night:

Q_{loss} = \frac{T_{cell} - T_{ambient}}{R_{thermal}} \times t_{night}

With multilayer insulation ($R_{thermal} \approx 10$ K·m²/W) and cell area A=10 m², $T_{ambient}=100$ K, $T_{cell}=1600$ K, $t_{night}=14×24×3600=1.21×10^6$ s:

Q_{loss} = \frac{1500}{10} \times 1.21e6 = 150 \times 1.21e6 = 1.815e8 \text{ J} = 50,400 \text{ kWh}

Mass of thermal storage (molten salt, latent heat ~500 kWh/m³) required: $V = 50,400/500 = 100.8$ m³ → mass ~200 tonnes—impractical. Hence need active insulation (regolith berm) and possibly lower standby temperature.

