APPENDIX E: AI DISCOVERY ALGORITHMS

E.1 AtomAgents Architecture Details

The multi-agent system is implemented using a federated learning framework with the following components:

· Explorer Agent: Uses genetic programming with mutation/crossover operators on composition vectors. Fitness function is the multi-objective score.
· Physics Agent: Queries a precomputed database of DFT results; if not found, schedules DFT job on HPC cluster.
· Thermo Agent: Runs CALPHAD using PyCalphad with TCHEA database.
· Kinetics Agent: Runs LAMMPS for diffusion and cascade simulations.
· ISRU Agent: Scores based on abundance, extraction energy, O₂ yield.
· Manufacturing Agent: Predicts printability using a neural network trained on AM process outcomes.

E.2 Graph Neural Networks for Alloy Properties

Crystal graph convolutional network (CGCNN) architecture:

· Node features: atomic number, group, period, electronegativity, etc.
· Edge features: bond distance, type.
· Convolution: $v_i^{(t+1)} = v_i^{(t)} + \sum_{j} \sigma(W_f [v_j^{(t)}; u_{ij}]) \odot g(W_s [v_j^{(t)}; u_{ij}])$
· Global pooling: $y = \text{MLP}(\sum_i v_i^{(T)})$

Trained on Materials Project data (130,000+ entries). Achieves MAE 0.03 eV/atom for formation energy.

E.3 CALPHAD Integration and Gibbs Free Energy Minimization

Given composition and temperature, Gibbs energy minimizer finds equilibrium phase fractions. The algorithm solves:

\min_{\{n^\phi\}} \sum_\phi n^\phi G_m^\phi

subject to $\sum_\phi n^\phi x_i^\phi = N_i$ (mass balance) and $\sum_i x_i^\phi = 1$ for each phase.

E.4 Multi-Objective Optimization and Pareto Fronts

The overall objective function:

F = w_1 \frac{\sigma_y}{\rho} + w_2 \log(\text{dpa}_{fail}) + w_3 \text{ISRU}_{score} + w_4 T_{max} - w_5 \text{Cost}_{import}

Weights are mission-dependent. Pareto front generated by NSGA-II algorithm.

E.5 Synergistic Aging Simulation

Coupled rate theory-phase field model:

\frac{\partial C_v}{\partial t} = \nabla \cdot (D_v \nabla C_v) + K_0 - R_{iv} C_i C_v - k_v^2 D_v C_v


\frac{\partial C_i}{\partial t} = \nabla \cdot (D_i \nabla C_i) + K_0 - R_{iv} C_i C_v - k_i^2 D_i C_i


\frac{\partial C_{He}}{\partial t} = \nabla \cdot (D_{He} \nabla C_{He}) + K_{He} - \text{trapping terms}

Coupled with phase field for precipitate evolution, including ballistic mixing.

